<h2>How to Build Your SEO YouTube Curriculum</h2>
<p>Do not subscribe to all 100 channels. That leads to information overload and zero action. Pick 6 to 10 channels based on your situation.</p>
<p><strong>If you are brand new to SEO:</strong> Start with Ahrefs, Neil Patel, and Google Search Central. These 3 cover fundamentals from different angles. Read our <a href="/blog/seo-for-beginners/">SEO for beginners guide</a> alongside them.</p>
<p><strong>If you run a local business:</strong> Add Ranking Academy, Whitespark, and Chris Palmer. Then read our <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local SEO guide</a> to put what you learn into action.</p>
<p><strong>If you are building a content site:</strong> Follow Authority Hacker, Niche Pursuits, and Matt Diggity. They teach content-driven SEO with real revenue data. Our <a href="/blog/content-marketing-strategy/">content marketing strategy guide</a> fills in the gaps.</p>
<p><strong>If you want to stay ahead on AI search:</strong> Watch Ahrefs and Marie Haynes for data on how <a href="/blog/ai-search-changing-seo/">AI search is changing SEO</a>. Our <a href="/blog/generative-engine-optimization-guide/">generative engine optimization guide</a> covers what these changes mean in practice.</p>
<p><strong>If you run an SEO agency:</strong> Nathan Gotch, Ryan Stewart, and Craig Campbell share real agency workflows. Their advice applies to both solo freelancers and small teams.</p>
<p><strong>If you optimize WordPress sites:</strong> Rank Math, WPBeginner, and Yoast cover plugin-based SEO. Pair their tutorials with our <a href="/blog/on-page-seo-guide/">on-page SEO guide</a>.</p>
<p><strong>If you evaluate SEO tools:</strong> Stewart Gauld and Metics Media compare tools side by side. Pair their reviews with our <a href="/best/best-free-seo-tools/">best free SEO tools</a> list for a complete picture.</p>
